Data Loading and Cleaning

weather_df = 
  rnoaa::meteo_pull_monitors(
    c("USW00094728"),
    var = c("PRCP", "TMIN", "TMAX"), 
    date_min = "2017-01-01",
    date_max = "2017-12-31") %>%
  mutate(
    name = recode(id, USW00094728 = "CentralPark_NY"),
    tmin = tmin / 10,
    tmax = tmax / 10) %>%
  select(name, id, everything())

Bootstrap and Plotting Pt 1

weather_df %>% 
  modelr::bootstrap(n = 1000) %>% 
  mutate(
    models = map(strap, ~lm(tmax ~ tmin, data = .x) ),
    results = map(models, broom::glance)) %>% 
  select(-strap, -models) %>% 
  unnest(results) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = r.squared)) + geom_density()

Plotting Pt 2

weather_df %>% 
  modelr::bootstrap(n = 1000) %>% 
  mutate(
    models = map(strap, ~lm(tmax ~ tmin, data = .x) ),
    results = map(models, broom::tidy)) %>% 
  select(-strap, -models) %>% 
  unnest(results) %>% 
  select(id = `.id`, term, estimate) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = term, 
    values_from = estimate) %>% 
  rename(beta0 = `(Intercept)`, beta1 = tmin) %>% 
  mutate(log_b0b1 = log(beta0 * beta1)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log_b0b1)) + geom_density()

Data Cleaning

murder_df=
twp_data %>%
janitor::clean_names() %>% 
mutate(
  state = replace(state, state== "wI", "WI")) %>% 
mutate(
  city_state= paste(city, state, sep= ",")) %>% 
mutate(
  victim_age = as.numeric(victim_age)) %>% 
filter(!city_state %in% c("Dallas,TX","Phoenix,AZ", "Kansas City,MO","Tulsa,AL" )) %>% 
filter(victim_race %in% c("White","Black")) %>% 
mutate(
    resolved = as.numeric(disposition == "Closed by arrest"))
## Warning in mask$eval_all_mutate(quo): NAs introduced by coercion

Description Within the original data set there are 52,719 observations and 12 variables. The variables names include: ‘uid’, ‘reported_date’, ‘victim_last’, ‘victim_first’, ‘victim_race’, ‘victim_age’, ‘victim_sex’, ‘city’, ‘state’, ‘lat’, ‘lon’, and ‘disposition’. This data was collected across different police department reports from 50 of the largest cities in the United States from the past decade. However, cities ‘Dallas,TX’, “Phoenix,AZ’,”Kansas City,MO’ and ‘Tulsa,AL’ were dropped from the data set due to them not reporting victim race or being a data entry mistake. The variable ‘victim_race’ was filtered to look at only homicides that reported a ‘White’ or ‘Black’ victim. In addition to the homicides classified as ‘Closed by arrest’ were recoded numerically under a new variable ‘resolved’. The final data set was named ‘muder_df’ and had 39,693 observations with 14 variables due to the generation of the ‘city_state’ and ‘resolved’ variables.

Linear Model

balt_murder_logfit = 
  murder_df %>% 
  filter(city_state == "Baltimore,MD") %>% 
  glm(resolved ~ victim_age + victim_race + victim_sex, data = ., family = binomial()) 
balt_murder_logfit %>% 
  broom::tidy() %>% 
  mutate(OR = exp(estimate)) %>%
  select(term, log_OR = estimate, OR, p.value) %>% 
  knitr::kable(digits = 3)

Within the city of Baltimore,MD, the odds of solving a homicide case for a male victim is 0.426 times higher than the odds of solving a homicide case for a female victim, adjusting for the victim’s sex and race. We are 95% confident that the true odds of solving a homicide case for a male victim within the Baltimore,MD is between 0.3241 and 0.5575.

All City Pipeline

all_city=
allcity_murder %>% 
  filter(term== "victim_sexMale") %>% 
  mutate(OR = exp(estimate),
         confh= exp(conf.high),
         confl= exp(conf.low)) %>%
  select(city_state, log_OR = estimate, OR, p.value, confl, confh)
all_city=
all_city %>% 
mutate(city_state= fct_reorder(city_state, OR))

Plotting

ggplot(all_city, aes(x= city_state, y= OR, color=city_state))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=confl, ymax= confh))+
  theme_classic()+ 
  theme(legend.position= "none")+
  ggtitle("Odds Ratio of Resolved Homicide Cases,Comparing Males to Females, in Large US Cities")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust= 0.5, size=12),
        axis.text.x.bottom = element_text(size= 7, angle= 90))+
    labs(x = "City",
        y= "Odds Ratio")

The estimated OR of resolved homicides, comparing male victims and female victims, for each of the 50 largest cities in the US were graphed in order of lowest to highest OR. New York, NY has the lowest OR for resolved cases of male victims compared to female victims, showing the odds of solving homicide cases for male victims compared to female victims is low. Whilst Albuquerque,NM has the highest, this demonstrates higher odds of solving homicide cases for male victims compared to female victims. Each was fitted with a error bar based upon the lowest and highest values from the estimates 95% confidence interval generated for the Odds Ratio.

Linear Modeling

bwt_model= lm(bwt ~ gaweeks, data=bwt_data)
bwt_data %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=gaweeks, y=bwt))+
  geom_point(alpha= 0.25)

Description A typical gestational period is approximately 40 weeks, with any infant born prior to 37 weeks being deemed as a preterm baby. Shorter gestational times are often associated with lower average birth weight of the child, and as a result we will hypothesize that the average birth weight of an infant will be dependent on the gestational period of the pregnancy. This graph above allows us to observe there is a possible positive relationship between the two variables as the shorter the gestational period is, the lower the birth weight is. Additionally, around 40 weeks there are increased observations around the average birth weight range (3000-4000 grams).

Comparing Models

bwt_modelme = lm(bwt~ blength + gaweeks, data = bwt_data)
bwt_modeltwi = lm(bwt~ bhead + blength + babysex+ bhead*blength + bhead*babysex + blength*babysex + bhead*blength*babysex, data = bwt_data)

RMSE

model_df = 
  crossv_mc(bwt_data, 100) %>% 
  mutate(
    train = map(train, as_tibble),
    test = map(test, as_tibble))

model_df = 
  model_df %>% 
  mutate(
    bwt_model_n   = map(train, ~lm(bwt ~ gaweeks, data = .x))) %>% 
  mutate(
    bwt_modelme_n = map(train, ~lm(bwt ~ blength + gaweeks, data = .x))) %>% 
  mutate(
    bwt_modeltwi_n= map(train, ~lm(bwt ~ bhead + blength + babysex+ bhead*blength + bhead*babysex +                          blength*babysex + bhead*blength*babysex, data = .x))) %>% 
  mutate(
    rmse_original    = map2_dbl(bwt_model_n, test, ~rmse(model = .x, data = .y)),
    rmse_maineffect  = map2_dbl(bwt_modelme_n, test, ~rmse(model = .x, data = .y)),
    rmse_interaction = map2_dbl(bwt_modeltwi_n, test, ~rmse(model = .x, data = .y)))
model_df %>% 
  select(starts_with("rmse")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    everything(),
    names_to = "model", 
    values_to = "rmse",
    names_prefix = "rmse_") %>% 
  mutate(model = fct_inorder(model)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = model, y = rmse)) + geom_violin()+
  ggtitle("Comparison of RMSE Values for Birth Weight Models")+
    labs(x = "Model",
        y= "RMSE")

Description RMSE was utilized to compare each of the three models due to it allowing for us to measure how far predicted values are from the observed values in a regression. With this, the larger the RMSE is, demonstrates a bigger difference between the predicted and observed values. As a result, it determines whether or not the regression is a good fit for the data. By observing violin graphs, it becomes evident that models with lower RSME are a better fit for the data. From this, model 3 (bwt_modeltwi/ Interaction) would be the best fit for this data from the models generated. However, the RMSE for each of the models, including ‘bwt_modeltwi/Interaction’, are quite high showing that there may be a better regression model that fits the data.
